After working for half a year on the
Pitt Program Council’s time capsule pro-
ject, 50 years of suspense will be nothing
for Michelle Wydra.

The project was Wydra’s idea, and
she will complete the job when she
buries the capsule full of student contri-
butions later this year. Then she will
spend the next 50 years anxiously await-
ing its opening by the class of 2050. ’

Originally designed to tie into this
year’s fund-raising event run by
Institutional Advancement, the time cap-

sule project grew into an event on its
own. ‘

Contributions will be on display in
the Conney M. Kimbo art gallery in the
William Pitt Union through Oct. 28.

Wydra, arts director of Program
Council, volunteered $2,600 of her bud-
get to get the project started.

Choosing from the surprisingly large
number of businesses that specialize in
time capsules, she hired Time Capsules,
Inc. to help.

Wydra then contacted each student
organization on campus and encouraged
groups to contribute an item to the cap-
sule that would preserve the memory of
their club.

Some political groups want to pre-
serve their current beliefs, in case the
issues or parties change in the future. '

“I want the class of 2050 to know
that the Republican party has always
stood for what’s right,” said Nick
Havens, President of the Pitt College
Republicans. ‘

Groups have been very responsive
— 27 have made donations and others
still plan to give. Proving that Pitt has a
diverse student population with a wide
variety of interests, there were contribu-

-tions from religious and political organi-

zations, Greek organizations, the radio
station, the Dental Science Club, Friends
of Animals and others.

