EDITORIAL
Feminism not limited to women

Yesterday, the Student
Government Board, as well as

several other - organizations,
hosted Sisterhood:
Empowerment Now, a confer--
ence aimed: at discussing

women’s issues on campus.’ The
brainchild of SGB President
Joan Snyder was attended by 34
women and one man.

After the referendum affair,
when SGB may have earned
itself a bad image, Snyder
should be praised for putting the
conference on as she mostly
coordinated it without the help

. of most‘ of the" board (especially

the male members).

The lone male who ‘attended,
junior Rob Brown, explained, “I
just think this stuff about femi-
nism isn’t exclusive to women.”
We should praise _Brown for
attending this conference for
valid reasons and not being
there just to get 34 phone num-
bers. He is exactly right —
equal rights for women is not
just a women’s issue, just as
racial equality is not just an
issue for minorities.

In fact, many of the early
feminists were men; for exam-
ple, William Lloyd Garrison,
known for his activities against
slavery, also proudly referred to

«himself as a feminist and cam-

paigned as hard for women’s
rights as he did for slavery’s
abolition. Most likely he also
faced the same criticism that he
was a “traitor to his race and/or
gender” that many modern-day
white male advocates of racial
and gender equality face.

At last week’s SGB meeting,
board member Jo’ie Taylor sug-

gested that the male board mem-

bers abstain from voting on the
allocation for this conference as
she believed that men should
have no say concerning alloca-
tions for a women’s conference.
While her viewpoint on this is
understandable, it was not nec-
essarily the best one as males
should — and do — have a say
in equal rights. V

Although this conference
was a step in the right direction,
more women — and men —
should have attended it. The
next time a conference such as
this one is held, the organizers
should make an effort to attract
both women and men. Not all
men are the selfish pigs that
many consider them to be; many
do care about women’s rights
and women’s issues.

After all, everyone, no mat-
ter what race or gender, has an
equal stake in the debate over
equal rights.

