A new way to spend Friday nights

Last year, I found a unique and interesting
way to laugh, smile and have an enjoyable time
on a Friday night, something that I especially
needed after having one of those typically
stressful weeks that most of us encounter.

My experience with Friday Night Irnprovs
started when I met this guy, Chris, on a bus ride
home from the mall on a Friday night. Chris
asked me ifl had any plans, so I told him about
the usual party and then he told me about

how much fun it was and suggest-
ing that I check it out sometime.
Comedy for only $2 sounded like a
neat idea to me and I had always
wanted to check out comic irnprov.
Now, I had my chance. »

So, the next Friday night rolled around and
a friend and I found ourselves heading down to
the basement of the Cathedral of Learning,
which was an interesting hideaway that I never
knew existed. We arrived exactly at 11 p.m.
and ended up sitting on the ﬂoor because the
place was packed — the theater area was cer-
tainly not spacious enough for this crowd.

I had never realized‘ how big of a thing this
actually was, as people were laughing and hav-
ing a good time before it even began!

The activities started with the host coming
out and telling the audience the basic rules of
Friday Night Irnprov. These rules included
having a good time and not booing any per-
formers.

From then on, it was hilarious. A person
would come out and explain the next game that
was going to be played. Then, members of the
audience volunteered to play. The games were
all different; varying from acting out a’ story to
playing musical and guessing games. AH of
them were played from a comical standpoint
—— no parts were actually serious. The per-
formers thought of their own themes and story
ideas and accepted audience members ideas as
well, using them to start each game. It was
mainly up to the performers to keep the stories
and ideas going. .

A favorite game of mine was one in which
a famous fairy tale was mixed up. The per-

