Panthers move to 5-1 with 42-26 win over Boston College

BRAD CUPRIK

Assistant Sports Editor

One of the only men smaller
than Pitt football head coach Walt
Harris had something of importance
at Saturday’s game against Boston
College.

A member of the Pitt band had a
piece of paper that Harris liked. It
was the definition of pride and" it
read, “Overwhelming desire to be
the best and doing it right the first
time.”

The Panthers may not be the
best team in the nation, but an
‘offensive outburst gave them a 42-

'26 win over the Eagles, equaling

last year’s win total of five.

It was the Panthers’ first win
over BC in four years, their last was
a 20-13 win in 1996 on a Thursday
night. -

Quarterback John Turman,
named the starter for the rest of the
season earlier in the week, respond-
ed to the announcement by throwing
for a career-high five touchdowns.

Running back Kevan Barlow
and wide receiver Antonio Bryant
could have won “best supporting
player” awards with career-highs of
209 yards rushing and 222 yards
receiving, respectively.

Barlow and Bryant each scored

two touchdowns, and sparked the
Panthers to a season-high 584 yards
of offense.

“I want to thank my football
players for bringing it and getting
