who was benched in the loss‘ to

Syracuse on Oct. 7 after fumbling‘ I

for the fifth time in a four-game
span.

Barlow came back with a
vengeance against BC, rushing for
209 yards on 25 carries, while
adding one rushing touchdown and
one receiving touchdown.

“[The running game] takes a ton
of pressure off of the passing
game,” Turman said. “That makes
my job a lot easier.”

Another thing that made
Turman’s job easier was the play of
the Pitt tight ends. ’

In the first five games, Pitt’s
tight ends had two catches, both by
Brennan Carroll. By the end of the
first half‘ of Saturday’s game, Pitt’s
tight ends ‘had two touchdown

' catches.

Kris Wilson, a redshirt fresh-

man, caught a 23-yard touchdown ~

pass from Turman in the first quar-
ter to put Pitt up 7-0, and Carroll

was on the receiving end of a 3-yard V

scoring play in the second quarter

that gave Pitt the lead for good at I

14-10.
“The tight ends were a big fac-

' tor [in my success],” Turman said.

“We worked on getting them; the
ball in practice and it carried over
to the game.” ,

With a 200-yard receiver and a
200-yard rusher, it appears that
Harris made the right decision when
choosing a starting quarterback and
putting the Pitt offense in the right
hands — John Turman’s.

 

